Class Project: Global Fishing Patterns¶

Roan Hollander

Introduction: Fishing on a Global Scale¶

I am looking at fishing patterns worldwide and addressing questions such as: How has the type of fishing gear used changed over time? How has global fishing effort changed from 1950-2017 and how has this been specific to each region? What are the patterns across the three main fishing sectors: Unpowered Artisinal, Powered Artisinal, and Industrial? All of these changes impact what the fishing effort has been across ecological functional groups, as each gear is used to target a different type of catch, and each catch varies regionally.

This is an important analysis because the state of today's global fisheries is increasingly under scrutiny. The timeline of this dataset is important, because after the second World War, technological advances made it possible for fishing fleets to stay at sea for much longer periods of time and catch more fish much more efficiently. This expanded fishing capacity greatly and made fisheries a more valuable economic commodity. Overfishing is depleting fish stocks everywhere, but it has different regional effects and causes and is caused by different gears. How do we analyze fisheries data to gain insights about where efforts to address overfishing and protect artisanal fisheries can be focused? Though my project cannot answer these questions fully, there are important dates and definitions to keep in mind when looking at temporal trends, which I elaborate upon later.

I got my data from The Institute of Marine and Antarctic Studies through Nature magazine. https://metadata.imas.utas.edu.au/geonetwork/srv/eng/catalog.search#/metadata/1241a51d-c8c2-4432-aa68-3d2bae142794

I have only found one paper in which this data was used: https://gmd.copernicus.org/articles/17/1/2024/. This article is looking at simulations of climate scenarios based on agricultural/fishery solutions and uses this data to project future fishing patterns.

Data Wrangling¶

For my analyses, I created several DataFrames that are groupings and subsections of the larger frames found in the data. This helped me look at Sector, Gear Type, and Region – my main categorical variables of interest for analyzing trends – more clearly and notice patterns. I joined a DataFrame with regional labels of all of the countries onto the main data set that I was using so I could analyze by that variable.

The relevant quantitative variables analyzed were vessel tonnage, vessel engine power, the effective fishing effort (kW of engine multiplied by days at sea).

Visualizing the Data¶

I conducted the visualization process in four steps to answer my research questions.

In order to see what the overall trends in vessel changes have been over time by region, I visualized how regional vessel power and tonnage changed from 1950 to 2017. I created both a line graph and a heatmap to create a comprehensive display.

Then, I visualized the overall mean effort in fishing for each functional group fished by using a bar graph. This provides insights into where changes in fishing effort are felt ecologically. After this, I looked at the changes in each type of gear used with multiple line plots. Each gear type targets a different functional group, therefore also distributing ecological impacts. Finally, I created a graph that visualizes the trends of change in vessel tonnage in each fishing sector.

1) Visualizing Regional Vessel Power and Tonnage Trends¶

I used line graphs to show where regional vessel tonnage and power has changed from 1950 to 2017. Certain regions, like the Indian Peninsula and North East Asia, have seen an increase in vessel tonnage whereas other regions, like North America had more of an increase in engine power. Important to note here is that the Law of the Sea , an international agreement created by the United Nations in 1982, took force in 1994. This is an interesting benchmark especially looking at the pattern of vessel engine power in North American Fleets, which peaked just before 1982 and began falling after 1994. This indicates that perhaps the Law of the Sea's regulations on overfishing had an impact on constraining the fleets of some UN member nations but not all.

2) Yearly Changes in Gear Used and Associated Vessel Power¶

I used a heatmap to show the changes in the vessel tonnage for each type of gear used. I also grouped some of the confusing gear names so they are aggregate and easier to understand and dropped names that were 'other' as they were not informative for the analyses here. Each gear type has a different ecological impact - the definitions below were taken from NOAA and the UN's FAO. They demonstrate the capacity of each gear type to gather a large quantity of fish and describe where the gear might be used, thus where the ecological impact is felt.


Bottom Trawling is a form of indusrial fishing that involves dragging huge nets across the seafloor, catching crabs and fish that live on the seafloor.
Dredges are another method that scrapes the seafloor and targets a variety of shellfish.
Falling Gear includes types of nets and baskets that are dropped atop of target species to capture them.
Gillnets are essentially a wall of net that is dragged through the water column, catching everything found.
Lift Nets are horizontal nets placed in the water column, then raised to catch fish above.
Lines are what we usually think of as fishing, casting a rod of some sort with a hook and bait at the end of it.
Midwater Trawling drags a huge net through the water column to catch the target species.
Pots and Traps are trap cages on the seafloor that are used to catch crustraceans.
Seine (Purse, Danish) fishing encircles a school of fish with a large net, catching them all in a cup-like shape that is pulled to the surface.

3) Changes Across Fishing Sectors¶

I used a line graph to analyze how the tonnage of vessels associated with each fishing sector has changed from 1950 to 2017. There are important definitions of what each kind of fishing is to keep in mind in order to understand how these changes have an ecological impact.

Industrial fishing is defined as fishing that uses a high level of technology and large boats to catch massive amounts of fish for commercial sale, and is usually run by large corporations. These factors make industrial fishing very high impact. Artisinal Unpowered fishing is a low-technology and small scale type of fishing that doesn't use motorized boats and is done more for daily needs than the commercial market that industrial fishing caters to. Artisinal Powered fishing is still smaller-scale fishing but uses powered vessels for a higher yield than artisinal unpowered fishing.

Given these definitions, changes in vessel tonnage per sector would have regional variations and high ecological consequences. The rise in industrial fishing has places lots of pressure on pelagic fish populations that are found on the High Seas and may drive artisinal unpowered fishers to use powered equipment or seek other professions if overfishing is too great.

Additional Analyses: Hypothesis Test for Correlation Between Gross Tonnage and Power¶

For my analyses, I wanted to see if there is a correlation between vessel power and gross vessel tonnage. To do this, I performed a hypothesis test.

Step 1: State the Null and Alternative Hypotheses¶

Null: the correlation between vessel tonnage and power is equal to zero, so there is no correlation

Alternative: the correlation between gross tonnage and vessel power is positive

$H_0: \rho{0} = 0$

$H_A: \rho{A} > 0$

Step 2: Calculate the Observed Statistic¶

In [25]:

regions_matched = regions_matched.dropna()
fishing_smaller = regions_matched[['GT', 'P']]
obs_stat = statistics.correlation(fishing_smaller["GT"], fishing_smaller["P"])

Step 4: Calculate P-value¶

In [29]:
pval = np.mean(np.array(null_dist) >= obs_stat)
pval
Out[29]:
0.0

Step 5: Drawing a Conclusion¶

The p-value calculated is 0, meaning that in the null distribution, there are no correlations aligned with the null hypothesis that are larger than the calculated correlation. This means that we can reject the null hypothesis and that there is in fact a correlation between gross vessel tonnage and vessel power. The calculated correlation is 0.65 which is strong and positive. As vessel power goes up gross vessel tonnage goes up, meaning that vessels are both larger and higher in count. Fleets steadily become more industrialized this way. Larger vessels have a higher capacity to stay at sea given their engine power, and they catch lots of fish and store them given their large size. This has a high ecological impact because fishing applies so much pressure to fisheries that it makes rebounding in population difficult. There are also ecosystem-wide effects of overfishing if a certain species is overfished, removing it from the food web.

Conclusions¶

These graphs show a wide range of changes in global fisheries that are all interconnected. When looking at vessel tonnage, we saw that in the Indian Peninsula is has been drastically increasing from 1950 to 2017. Vessel power increased in this region and in North East Asia as well, revealing trends that reinforce the growing amount of industrial fishing. Vessel power in North America spiked greatly from the mid 1970s to mid 1980s before declining again, possibly because of regulatory action and the Law of the Sea being enacted due to fisheries collapse.

When we look at changes from 1950 to 2017, we can see that gillnets, bottom and midwater trawling, purse seines, and longlines have increased in terms of their respective vessel tonnages. These gears are used to target mostly pelagic and demersal fish, and when looking at the bar chart of where total fishing efforts have been directed between functional groups, these are the groups that have been the most highly fished. This means that the rise in those specific gear types has put more pressure on those functional groups.

Since 1950, industrial fishing has drasically increased, which makes sense considering the increases in trawling, purse seine and gillnet gears that are commonly used by industrial fleets to target deep water and open ocean fish. Artisinal powered fishing has increased as well, but artisinal unpowered fishing has declined. This is likely because economic pressure for fishermen to catch higher yields has encouraged industrialization and powering of their fleets, and overfishing causes fishermen to pursue fish in harder to reach areas where powered boats are needed.

My hypothesis test shows that there is a strong positive correlation between vessel power and gross tonnage, showing the pattern of how fleets become more industrialized and extractive.

All of this data provides insights into regional trends, which play into sector trends, gear usage, and the functional group targeted. For example, pelagic fish can only be caught in the open ocean, so targeting this group requires industrial fleets that use trawling and purse seines.
